  "id": "019d23ff-b189-7181-880c-758d6abb564a",
  "content": "# Devcontainer Setup Script Duplicate Execution — Research Findings\n\n## Problem Statement\nThe devcontainer `postStartCommand` (post-start.sh) runs twice during container startup. The bash-based lock/done-marker mechanism fails to reliably prevent re-execution or detect what's already set up.\n\n## Root Cause Analysis\n\n### Why it runs twice\nVS Code fires `postStartCommand` both during container start AND during window attach/reconnect. This is by-design behavior in the devcontainer spec — `postStartCommand` runs \"each time the container starts successfully\" and VS Code's lifecycle detection is imperfect.\n\n### Why current protection fails\n1. **mkdir lock** — survives SIGKILL (stale lock blocks future runs), doesn't auto-cleanup\n2. **/tmp done markers** — cleared on container restart, not visible across container recreations\n3. **set -euo pipefail** — can cause silent early exit before done marker is written (line 203 is last step)\n4. **Fundamental flaw**: tracking \"have I run?\" instead of \"is it done?\" — lock files and done markers answer the wrong question\n\n## Approaches Evaluated\n\n### A) Devcontainer Features API\n- `install.sh` runs at build time (Docker layer, truly once)\n- Lifecycle hooks in Features suffer the SAME duplicate execution problem\n- Good for: moving installs to build time. Does NOT solve runtime idempotency.\n\n### B) Systemd / Supervisord\n- supervisord: good fit for service management (start is idempotent), doesn't require PID 1\n- s6-overlay: requires PID 1, conflicts with devcontainer's `overrideCommand: true`\n- Only solves service lifecycle, not one-time setup tasks\n\n### C) Taskfile (RECOMMENDED)\n- `status:` checks express \"what does done look like?\" — real idempotency\n- Dependency graph handles ordering automatically\n- Parallel execution of independent tasks built in\n- Checksum fingerprinting detects when source scripts change\n- Combined with flock for concurrency protection = complete solution\n- Real-world example: Megabyte Labs devcontainer uses Taskfile for all setup orchestration\n\n### D) Docker ENTRYPOINT\n- Runs once per `docker start`, before postStartCommand\n- Requires `overrideCommand: false` (conflicts with devcontainer defaults)\n- Good for per-boot setup, not for service recovery\n\n### E) JSON State Machine\n- Fine-grained per-step tracking with invalidation policies (per-boot, per-version, permanent)\n- Over-engineered for this use case when Taskfile status: checks achieve the same thing\n\n### F) flock(1) vs mkdir\n- flock is strictly superior in containers: auto-cleanup on SIGKILL, no stale locks\n- mkdir lock survives SIGKILL → stale lock blocks all future runs\n- flock pattern: `exec 200>/var/run/corvia-post-start.lock; flock -n 200 || exit 0`\n\n## Decision: Taskfile + flock\n\nReplace bash orchestration with Taskfile where each task has `status:` checks testing actual state (port responding? binary exists? auth valid?) rather than marker files. Wrap entry point in flock for concurrency. Move installs to Dockerfile/post-create where possible.\n\nKey benefits: real idempotency, parallel execution, granular recovery, no /tmp dependency, debuggable with `task --list`.\n\n## References\n- Dev Container spec lifecycle hooks: https://containers.dev/implementors/json_reference/\n- BashFAQ/045 locking: https://mywiki.wooledge.org/BashFAQ/045\n- Taskfile status checks: https://taskfile.dev/usage/\n- VS Code devcontainer issue on duplicate postStartCommand\n- Megabyte Labs devcontainer Taskfile example",
